comments.text:
Why do we keep investing energy in debating historical personalities—elevating some to near-divine status while belittling others—as if our salvation depends on their actions? Allah will not ask us about Abu Bakr, Umar, Uthman, or Ali (may Allah be pleased with them all). He will ask us whether we followed His Book.

The Qur’an warns us not to dispute about the people of the past, saying:

"Tilka ummatun qad khalat; laha maa kasabat wa lakum maa kasabtum; wa laa tus’aloona ‘ammaa kaanoo ya’maloon"
"That was a nation who passed away. Theirs is what they earned, and yours is what you earn. And you will not be asked about what they did." (Qur’an 2:134, repeated in 2:141)

Yet today, some speakers and scholars stir division by attacking or sanctifying historical figures. This is not the prophetic way. The Prophet (ﷺ) united the Ummah under tawheed and the Qur'an—not tribalism, personalities, or political factions.

Yes, Hadith literature is a valuable scholarly tradition, but we must remember that it was collected and compiled generations after the Prophet, and is vulnerable to human error, bias, and fabrication. Even “authentic” Hadith should be critically evaluated, especially when they promote divisiveness or contradict Qur’anic principles. Some narrations speak of unseen matters and future events—knowledge the Qur’an declares belongs only to Allah (Qur’an 31:34).

Let’s return to what matters:

"Inna ad-deena ‘inda Allahil-Islam"
“Indeed, the religion with Allah is Islam.” (Qur’an 3:19)

Sunni and Shia are historical labels, not divine commands. The Prophet never called his followers by these names. True Islam is Qur’an-centered, peace-oriented, and unifying. Our scholars and leaders should guide us back to what truly matters: worship, justice, character, and unity under the Qur’an.
